cohort.reelThemIn: I eat leftover sushi for breakfast.
cohort.bio:
Prior to becoming a software developer, I worked full time in distillation and brewing. Like software development, these careers rely on an attention to detail and ensuring all processes are accounted for in order to ensure everything works together seamlessly.

I had been interested in software development since dipping my toes in basic website design during internships in college. I enjoy using both my creativity and problem solving skills to create useful tools. Immediately after beginning to learn Javascript basics, I was hooked. I love new challenges and never want to stop learning.

cohort.reelThemIn: Positively impacting the criminal justice system by teaching incarcerated individuals IT skills!
cohort.bio: I am a Software Developer who recently transitioned from a career in Law Enforcement. My interest in technology was sparked from a prison program at San Quentin State Prison that taught inmates how to code. I believe programs like these are a great asset to rehabilitating inmates and society as a whole. I decided to learn software development for myself. Software development allows me to continuously learn, while giving me the opportunity to put my problem-solving skills to work. I am excited to see where this new career path takes me.

cohort.reelThemIn: I try to find the positive in every situation.

cohort.reelThemIn: Technology is best when it brings people together.
cohort.bio: I am a graduate of the Howard University Class of 2020, and received my degree in Political Science. Upon graduation, and in the very beginning of the pandemic I decided I'd like to pursue a career in Tech. I have always been fascinated with Software Engineering and now I would finally have the chance to take the plunge. If I'd be forced to be home all day, why. not attempt a new skill that would open doors for years to come. Fortunately, I had family in the Nashville Metropolitan area and an uncle that recently graduated from NSS. I applied, got in and moved to Nashville the following day, a year and a few awesome languages later (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, React, Python, SQL & Django). I'm extremely excited to start my career in tech, especially as a Black Woman. We are marginalized in Tech and I hope to open doors for those who come after me.

cohort.reelThemIn: Software development is easy. It's like riding a bike, except the bike is on fire. And you're on fire. And everything's on fire. And you're in Hell.
cohort.bio:
I've worked in technology my entire life. I started with a long career in the Air Force as a cyberspace operations officer, followed by various roles in security for defense contractors and state government. In my most recent job, I was a technical trainer. One common thread in all my positions has been the desire and need to inject automation everywhere I could, which drove me to learn basic scripting and coding on my own. I fell in love with code way back then, and that drove me to this career change. NSS has given me the whole package - not just learning the languages, but more importantly, the 'soft skills' that employers demand today: how to learn new languages, problem deconstruction and problem-solving skills, a hunger for learning, being curious, not being afraid to ask for help, and a team mentality while still being independent - among others. For this, I am grateful to everyone at NSS and to my peers in Cohort 54. I would not have been as successful in this endeavor without you all.

I am now ready to put it all to the test; I think my security background coupled with my new developer skills will help make the applications I work on be more secure. So, I'm looking forward to joining an amazing team with a great company in my first role as a Software Engineer and continue my learning.

cohort.reelThemIn: "If you had the chance to change your fate, would you?"  Music Teacher => Developer
cohort.bio:
Growing up, much to my parents chagrin, I was a tinkerer. I would find electronics around the house and disassemble/reassemble them. Sometimes, even successfully! This evolved into working more with software after I built my first pc sometime in middle school. Even though I had never been a technology professional, I always tried to keep up with it. I would always be looking for the best software I could use to help my students.

After working for 10+ years as a music teacher, I felt the call to pursue my passion of technology. I searched for which program produces the most successful students and discovered Nashville Software School. I have not only learned how to code while here, I completely reshaped how I think. I see the world more analytically than I did before. When I see some applications, for example, I try to figure out the data structure/flow for how that application is constructed. I've enjoyed every day of learning at NSS and hope to continue that feeling as a junior software developer in the Nashville area.
